{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4d938c6a-991a-4808-acbd-3cdb10dba435","content":"Here's what you need:\n\n### 1. `Directory.Build.props` (at solution root, for consistency)\n\n```xml\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n  <ItemGroup>\n    <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" />\n  </ItemGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n`EnableMSTestRunner` activates the built-in Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner in MSTest 3.x. `OutputType Exe` is required because each test project now produces a self-contained test executable.\n\n### 2. Each test `.csproj` — remove VSTest-specific packages\n\nRemove these if present (they're VSTest infrastructure, now unnecessary):\n```xml\n<!-- REMOVE these -->\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"MSTest.TestAdapter\" />\n```\n\nKeep `MSTest.TestFramework` (or `MSTest` meta-package if you use it — 3.8.0 already bundles the runner).\n\n### 3. Package version for TrxReport\n\nIf you use Central Package Management (`Directory.Packages.props`), add:\n```xml\n<PackageVersion Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.5.3\" />\n```\n\nOtherwise, pin the version directly in `Directory.Build.props`.\n\n### 4. CI command change\n\n```diff\n- dotnet test --logger trx\n+ dotnet test -- --report-trx\n```\n\n`--logger trx` is a VSTest concept. With Microsoft.Testing.Platform, arguments after `--` are forwarded to the test runner. `--report-trx` is provided by the TrxReport extension.\n\nTo control the output path: `-- --report-trx --report-trx-filename MyResults.trx`\n\n### Summary of changes\n\n| Area | Old (VSTest) | New (Testing Platform) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Runner | `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk` + adapter | `EnableMSTestRunner=true` |\n| OutputType | Library (default) | **Exe** |\n| TRX logging | `--logger trx` | `-- --report-trx` (+ NuGet package) |\n| Test command | `dotnet test` | `dotnet test` (still works) |\n\n> **Note:** On .NET 8 SDK, `dotnet test` uses a VSTest-compatibility bridge to discover and run the test executables. This works transparently. .NET 9+ SDK adds native protocol support via `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>`, which you can adopt when you upgrade.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f3ee928d-60ae-4a3c-8445-f185ae499754","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate their MSTest 3.8.0 test projects from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform. Let me provide a clear, concise answer based on my knowledge of this migration path.\n\nKey changes needed:\n\n1. **Project-level changes**: Enable Microsoft.Testing.Platform in each test project by adding `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` to the project file. With MSTest 3.8.0, the MSTest runner is built-in, so no extra package is needed.\n\n2. **Consistent properties via Directory.Build.props**: Since they want consistency across all 3 projects, use a `Directory.Build.props` file.\n\n\n3. **CI command changes**: The `dotnet test` command needs adjustment—`--logger trx` becomes `--report-trx` when using Microsoft.Testing.Platform. For TRX report generation with MSTest 3.8.0, you'll need the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` package. the `--logger trx` syntax doesn't work with the new testing platform, so you'd pass `-- --report-trx` instead, or enable `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` to get the standard `dotnet test` integration working. For the project setup, I need to set those properties in the project file along with adding the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` package.\n\nActually, I'm realizing `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` was added in .NET 9, so with .NET 8 SDK the approach is different—`dotnet test` still works but uses a compatibility bridge by default, and I might need to pass arguments after `--` to use the native platform directly.\n\nLet me think through the practical setup for .NET 8 with MSTest 3.8.0: I'd configure the project properties to enable the MSTest runner and set the output type to executable, then either pass `--report-trx` after `--` when running `dotnet test`, or just run the test executable directly. I should also mention the `--report-trx-filename` option for controlling the output file name, and verify that `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` is the right package to add for TRX report support with MSTest 3.8.0.","outputTokens":2292,"requestId":"4815:23D333:30E35F7:3570D4A:69FBE1D4"},"id":"203edcca-5a72-44d6-a966-e79f2d41453b","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:51:12.031Z","parentId":"04876d5a-8b2e-4fdf-b4fc-f8ad3abd7610"}
